Text
Okay just something that I caught that really annoyed me...(cause I'm fixing ty
typos.) Don't put anything in a description that doesn't have anything to do wi
Only tell what is there...not or somethings might be...may be could be phrases
don't use the word here. They are in the room it should be obvious...included
in next message is the general building guidelines of another mud I'd like
them followed for the most part here...also would like to appoint a head "check
"checker" (formerly was one of aowans jobs but she hasn't been around)
~

Sender  Kyorlin~
Date    Fri Dec 27 19:21:57 2002~
To      All~
Subject BUILDING GUIDELINES~
Voting 0
Yesvotes ~
Novotes ~
Abstentions ~
Text
ROOM STANDARDS                                                                                    
                                                                                                  
1  - No use of the word 'you' or any of its forms.  If you are standing in a
 room, you don't need to put yourself in it in the description                                                          
2  - No use of the word 'here'.  If you are here, you don't need to be
 redundant, also, when using scry you are 'there' not 'here'.                                                                 
3  - No directional sentences.  You have no way of knowing how a
 person will enter a room or which direction it would be from.                                                                      
4  - No contractions.  They just don't look nice.                                                 
5  - Proper spelling is very important, as is grammer and the proper
 use of words.                
6  - Room names, sectors and flags must make sense and be in tune
 with the description of the room.                                                                                                 
7  - Extras follow the same guidelines as rooms.                                                  
8  - Exdscs must be put on each and every exit, no exceptions.                                                     
9  - A good description is between 4 and 10 lines long.  Short 
descriptions make a room look unfinished, long descriptions 
can become tedious.  Extras can take care of things mentioned
 in the description that need further describing rather than putting
 them in the main description.            
10 - Varying sentence length will make a description read much 
more smoothly than long run-on sentences or short choppy ones.                                                                       
                                                                                            
~

